Now we use the data that we have:

$$\begin{aligned}
 \text{Current Assets} & = 1.3 \cdot \$955\\
 & = \boxed{\$1,241.50}
\end{aligned}$$

Current Assets are **$1,241.50**

Now we use the data that we have:

$$\begin{aligned}
 \text{Net Income} & = \%8.3 \cdot \$7210\\
 & = \boxed{\$598.43}
\end{aligned}$$

The Net Income is **$598.43**

The next step is to substitute with the information that we have:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Equity}& = \dfrac{\$598.43}{17.50\%}\\

 & = \boxed{\$3,419.60}
\end{aligned}$$

Total Equity is **$3,419.60**

*Third step:*
$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{Total Equity}}{\text{Long-term Debt}}& = \frac{1-\text{Long-term Debt Ratio}}{\text{Long-term Debt Ratio}}
\\
\\
{\text{Long-term Debt}}& = \frac{\text{Total Equity}\cdot\text{Long-term Debt Ratio}}{1-\text{Long-term Debt Ratio}}
\end{aligned}$$

With this formula rearranged we can calculate the Long-term Debt:

$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{Long-term Debt}}& = \frac{\$3,419.60\cdot{0.35}}{1- 0.35}\\
& = \boxed{\$1,841.32}
\end{aligned}$$
 The Long-term Debt is **$1,841.32**
